#!/usr/bin/env python3
"""Worldbook: add tiered city labels to the Countries reference layer.

Mike's ask: "the countries layer is a bit plain now, maybe we should include
major and midsize cities (in different sized fonts and or styles depending
upon size) ... you tell me" - explicit design delegation.

Data: Natural Earth ne_50m_populated_places (1251 places), filtered/tiered by
population and capital status:
  Tier 1 (visible from world view, minzoom 0)   - national capitals and
                                                   megacities (pop >= 3M).
                                                   276 places. Noto Sans Bold,
                                                   size 13.
  Tier 2 (visible from zoom 2)                  - other major cities,
                                                   pop >= 750k. 307 places.
                                                   Noto Sans Regular, size 11.
  Tier 3 (visible from zoom 3.5)                 - midsize cities,
                                                   pop >= 200k. 279 places.
                                                   Noto Sans Italic, size 9.5 -
                                                   so the globe doesn't turn
                                                   into alphabet soup at world
                                                   view, and the type style
                                                   itself signals hierarchy
                                                   (bold capitals -> plain
                                                   majors -> italic midsize),
                                                   not just size.
  (389 smaller places excluded entirely - too minor for this map's scale.)

Each tier is its own circle+symbol layer pair (6 layers total: cities-dot-N /
cities-label-N) rather than one layer with a zoom expression, because minzoom
is a plain, bulletproof layer property (no ambiguity about zoom-in-filter
support in MapLibre) AND because a symbol hidden by opacity/zoom-expression
below its "reveal point" would still occupy the shared collision index and
could block a neighboring label from placing - a separate layer that simply
hasn't reached its minzoom yet never has that problem. Same reasoning as the
existing per-tier country-label zoom-gating already in this codebase.

Dot + text colored to match the existing country-labels ink/halo exactly
(#3a3226 ink, white halo) for visual consistency with the rest of the
Countries layer. symbol-sort-key follows the same "-1 * importance"
convention as country-labels (lower number = higher collision priority),
scaled small (-1..-3) so cities generally defer to country-name labels at
world view (which use size-based sort keys with much larger magnitude) but
still rank sensibly against each other.

Wired into the existing "_isCountriesRef" toggle inside setLayer() - the same
block that already shows/hides the border glow layers - so cities are
Countries-only: hidden during satellite/topo rasters, every choropleth and
flow layer, Library Globe, and subnational drill-down, exactly like the glow
layers they sit next to.

Idempotent, pure ASCII source.
Usage: python3 worldbook_cities_layer.py index.html index.html
"""
import sys

INP = sys.argv[1] if len(sys.argv) > 1 else "index.html"
OUT = sys.argv[2] if len(sys.argv) > 2 else "index.html"
text = open(INP, encoding="utf-8").read()

